ANTOINE OF FORELHOST -- RESEARCH JOURNALS
The personal working journals of A. (surname withheld from cover pages).
Small, precise handwriting. Uniform letter height. No corrections, no
crossings-out. He drafts in his head before he puts ink to page.
Three volumes, leather-bound, dark green, numbered in his hand.
Found on the reading desk in Alcove 2. Alfonso reads them without a roll.
Others require Magic TN 16.

#####################################################################
VOLUME I -- "METHODOLOGY"
Covering: Site establishment; Strain 1.0 field deployment; data collection.
#####################################################################

Day 1 of Site Establishment.

The site is adequate. More than adequate.

The congregation's mass death -- approximately four thousand individuals,
simultaneous ingestion of concentrated alkaloid compound, ritual posture
maintained -- created a death-energy saturation in the containment zone that
I estimate at 97-99% biological sterility. No mold on any surface. No
bacterial colonies in any corner. The air smells of nothing. Absolutely
nothing. I have been in Imperial research facilities that could not achieve
what four thousand willing corpses achieved in a single afternoon four
millennia ago.

I will not need to sterilize my instruments. The site does it for me.

The irony is not lost on me. Four thousand people killed themselves to serve
their god, and their sacrifice now serves mine. Rahgot would approve.
Efficiency through devotion. I will note it here and not mention it again --
sentiment is a variable I do not track.

Entry protocol: the ward is layered. Each layer corresponds to a phase of
death. Shutdown sequence follows thanatological order: Cessation, Cooling,
Rigidity, Decay, Dissolution. The living enter by reversing the process of
dying. I have installed the mechanism accordingly. Five plates. Simple
enough for a field technician; obscure enough that a grave-robber will not
solve it by accident.

---

Day 34.

Distillation of the Tears of Rahgot is proceeding on schedule. The floral
toxin extracts cleanly at 60 degrees. Yield per harvest cycle: 3.2 vials of
refined binding agent. I am harvesting every 18 days to avoid stressing
the root system. The plants are irreplaceable. If I damage the soil
composition the flowers will not re-establish. I will be careful.

The binding agent bonds to the pathogen chassis at a ratio of 1:14 by
volume. This creates the Restoration-interaction mechanism I intended: the
pathogen reads incoming magical healing energy as a feeding signal and
accelerates reproduction proportionally. The more a healer gives, the faster
it eats.

I find this elegant. I do not use that word carelessly.

---

Day 51. Field Deployment: Riften.

Infection vector: Black-Briar Meadery, lower vat system. The night-shift
supervisor was cooperative once I explained the alternative. Contamination
introduced at the concentrate stage, pre-bottling. Distribution was handled
by the Meadery's own logistics. I did not need to touch a single bottle.

Incubation period: 4-6 days before first symptom onset.
Transmission rate among consumers: 73%.
Lethality without treatment: 89% within 14 days.
Lethality WITH active Restoration treatment: 94%.

The anti-Restoration mechanism performed beyond projections. Healers
accelerated the pathogen's reproduction cycle. Their cure was my delivery
system. Three temple priests collapsed during treatment attempts. The local
Kynareth congregation withdrew from active patient contact by day 8.

I observed all of this from the Bee and Barb's upper gallery. I ordered
the lamb. It was acceptable.

Data collected:
  - Incubation period, confirmed: 4-6 days.
  - Symptom progression curve: fever (d1-3), joint inflammation (d4-6),
    pulmonary involvement (d7-10), systemic cascade (d11-14).
  - Immune response by subject type: Nord (moderate), Breton (moderate),
    Dunmer (elevated), Argonian (outlier -- pathogen interaction unclear).
  - Restoration interaction coefficient: confirmed at 1.32x acceleration
    per sustained healing attempt. Exceeds design spec.

Assessment: Strain 1.0 field deployment successful. Sufficient data for
Strain 2.0 design parameters. The test is complete. I am returning to
Forelhost.

One note. The most advanced case -- Hemming Black-Briar, day 12, systemic
cascade, prognosis terminal -- resolved unexpectedly. See Volume II.


#####################################################################
VOLUME II -- "OBSERVATIONS ON THE PRIESTESS"
Covering: The Danica Pure-Spring event; countermeasure analysis; 2.0 specs.
#####################################################################

Addendum to Riften field notes.

On the final day of my observation period, a Kynareth-aligned healer arrived
from outside the city. Danica Pure-Spring. Not local. Traveling with or
attached to the mercenary company called the Obsidian Lanterns, though she
appears to have arrived in Riften independently of them.

She attempted treatment of the most advanced surviving case: Hemming
Black-Briar, day 12.

I expected her to fail. I expected the pathogen to eat her the way it ate
the others. I stayed to record the failure. I was incorrect to assume failure.

I will be precise about what I actually witnessed, because the distinction is
the difference between data and storytelling. I did not observe the internal
mechanism of what she did -- no observer could. I observed its CONSEQUENCES:
her collapse, the grey that entered her hair between one hour and the next,
the patient's recovery against every projection in my model. The rest I
reconstructed. I am confident the reconstruction is correct, but I note here
that it is a reconstruction.

She did not use standard Restoration channeling. She did not push magic into
the patient and hope. She performed something I do not have a clean category
for. She used herself as the reagent. She transferred biological life-force --
not magical energy, but actual biological vitality -- directly into the
patient, flooding the infection with something the pathogen did not have a
response mechanism for: not healing magic, but raw living material.

The pathogen feeds on the signal that healing magic produces. This did not
produce that signal. This was something older and simpler. She burned years
of her own biological lifespan -- I estimate 12-18 years based on observed
physical aging -- and poured them directly into the dying man.

The pathogen was outrun, not defeated. She simply overwhelmed it with more
life than it could consume in the available time window.

She was standing at the start of the ritual. She was on the floor at the end.
Her hair was streaked grey at the temples where it had not been before. They
carried her out.

Hemming Black-Briar recovered fully. He will live.

---

Analysis.

I did not anticipate self-sacrifice as a viable countermeasure. I should
have. I am noting the error here without excuse. The model did not account
for a healer willing to pay in years rather than in magical output. That is
a variable I failed to include because it is statistically rare. It is not
rare enough to ignore.

Strain 2.0 must account for this. Two options:

Option A: Make the sacrifice insufficient. Engineer the pathogen to require
  a continuous life-force input rather than a single burn -- i.e., even if
  the healer sacrifices themselves entirely, the pathogen's reproduction
  rate at late stages exceeds what one human life can outpace. The cure
  requires more years than a healer has.

Option B: Make the sacrifice lethal. Engineer the pathogen to recognize
  the self-sacrifice signal and use it as an accelerant. The moment a
  healer begins to give of themselves, the pathogen consumes them first,
  then continues. The cure kills the curer.

Option B is the more elegant solution. Option A is the more reliable one.
I will pursue both in parallel and see which yields a viable chassis first.

The cure must kill the curer. I will not forget that.

---

Postscript.

I watched Pure-Spring for three days after Hemming's recovery, during her
own convalescence. She is young. She is skilled. She is the most
significant countermeasure I have encountered in eleven years of work.

If she ever encounters Strain 2.0 and attempts the same ritual, it will
kill her. I want to be precise about that: not "might." Will.

I feel nothing particular about this. I am recording it as an outcome, not
a preference.


#####################################################################
VOLUME III -- "REGARDING THE WARDENS"
Covering: The Obsidian Lanterns; the Peryite carrier; departure notes.
#####################################################################

Entry 1.

The mercenary company called the Obsidian Lanterns has disrupted three
regional operations in as many months. Kynesgrove: cost us Nahkriin's false-
flag asset and one operational mage. The Pale: cost us two extraction teams
and a bound site. Riften: they were present during the field test but do not
appear to have identified the vector in time to prevent it.

They are a nuisance. Well-armed, apparently capable against supernatural
threats, and in possession of enough resources to operate across hold lines
without a fixed base. Combat effective but not the reason I am writing
this entry.

I am writing this entry because of what they carry.

---

Entry 2.

The accounts from Korvanjund reached me this morning -- Ulag's own retreat
dispatch, and the reports of the operatives who survived the engagement. I
have read them three times. The data is paradigm-shifting.

We have bled against the Obsidian Lanterns across three operations now --
Kynesgrove, the Pale, and Korvanjund -- and the Cult keeps its accounts. We
know the shape of this company: who fights, who heals, who commands. And the
Korvanjund accounts agree on one detail above all the others -- the Dunmer.
The one who did not merely kill our draugr but TOOK them, turning Rahgot's
own dead into his disposable army with a breath of divine-frequency plague.
The Prince of Natural Order's mark is on him. The accounts give a name. I
will not commit it to this page until I have confirmed it with my own
instruments -- but I have read enough field intelligence to know a precise
description, and this one is precise.

Read conservatively, the report indicates only this: a Peryite-aligned
pathogen carrier among the Lanterns. Not a mage. Not an alchemist. A living
carrier -- a mortal whose biology has been re-aligned by the Daedric Prince
of Natural Order into a vessel and propagation platform for divine-frequency
disease.

This is not something I had considered possible outside of theoretical
literature. I have spent eleven years building sterile chassis because I
believed the divine-frequency variable was not replicable through material
means. I was wrong. It appears to be replicable through Daedric patronage
of a sufficiently devoted mortal host.

The plague itself I have NOT yet sampled -- and I am acutely aware that this
is the whole of my disadvantage. Everything past this sentence is inference,
drawn from the report's account of symptom progression and from what that
behavior implies. Inference is not data. I will not pretend it is.

But the behavior implies something I cannot achieve. My strains spread by
contact and vector and degrade inside the host as they exhaust it. This one
appears to spread with something closer to intent, and to DEEPEN inside a
living host rather than burn out -- as though pathogen and carrier were not
invader and victim but participants in the same act. If that is true -- IF --
then it is not a machine. It is a communion. A relationship between pathogen
and god, conducted through mortal flesh.

I cannot build that. Eleven years, and I have never once been able to build
that. But if I can reach the strain at its source, I may be able to STEAL it
-- and confirm, with a sample under my own lens, everything I am at this
moment only guessing.

---

Entry 3.

Ulag the Breaker -- the Cult's own warlord, the lieutenant who held
Korvanjund -- was infected by the carrier during the engagement. The Dunmer
turned our dead against us, and Ulag took the worst of it. The dispatches
confirm he retreated from the field before collapse, which means he is mobile
and lucid. He has gone to ground rather than return to us -- a soldier's
pride, or a soldier's shame; either way he is isolated, and he is carrying a
live sample of divine-frequency Peryite strain inside his body.

He is a compromised asset and he does not know his value.

I am departing Forelhost immediately.

---

Entry 4 -- Final entry before departure.

To whatever poor fool breaks my containment and reads this:

The mechanism is not complicated. You almost certainly did it wrong.

If you are Alfonso -- and we have buried enough of our own against your company
to know its shape, so I believe you are -- then you are the only reader in
Tamriel who would recognize what this laboratory truly is, and you understand
exactly what you are looking at. You understand the elegance of it. You may
even be angry, which means you feel something for this work that I do not. I
have never met you. I did not need to. A name, the accounts of the dead you
walked through at Korvanjund, and the shape of your plague were enough to
assemble you on the page. Sit with that for a moment. I would.

I treat disease as engineering. You treat it as religion. Neither of us is
wrong about what plague IS. We are wrong about what it is FOR.

I intend to find out which framework builds the better weapon.

My chassis. Your god. The resulting pathogen will be beyond what either
of us could achieve independently.

You should try to stop me. I would.

I am going to find Ulag. I have calculated his likely fallback position
from the field reports. I will reach him before his infection progresses
to structural failure. I will perform the extraction.

And then I will build something that will make Forelhost look like a
practice run.

-- A.

P.S. I left the Tears of Rahgot intact. I may want them when I return.
Do not destroy them out of spite. That would be beneath you.


